==Old English==
===Etymology===
From an early form [[haebuc]], from Germanic ''*habokaz'', from Indo-European ''*kep-'' ‘seize’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[havek]] (Frisian [[hauk]]), Old Saxon [[hauk]] (Dutch [[havik]]), Old High German [[habuh]] (German [[Habicht]]), Old Norse [[haukr]] (Swedish [[hök]]).  The word is related to a Slavic word for a bird of prey (Russian [[кобец]], Polish [[kobuz]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'havok/

===Noun===
'''hafoc''' ''m'' (''pl'' '''hafocas''')
# a [[hawk]]

